		<hr size="1">I have never seen "would not take hold" when conjuring a familiar. It kind of looks like you already had one so you couldn't have a second. However, if you are a charm class and you try to charm a second mob, it says something like "You cannot have two pets at once".<BR>I would try zoning to see if the thing should will come back to you. I never click off the buff. It takes too much mana to get him back <img src='http://www.everlore.com/gimages/smile.gif' width=15 height=15 align=middle></P><P>Anyway, I will have to try that later to see what happens on my wizzy. Since I fizzle so much when casting, I am always so glad when it finally casts, I don't have time to cast it again before the spell is un-memorized. <img src='http://www.everlore.com/gimages/smile.gif' width=15 height=15 align=middle></P><P>On a more general note about familiars....I almost always do a /pet get lost to get rid of the familiar, but keep the benefits of the buff. I didn't use my familiar for a long time after I got it because I didn't see the benefit. Now I see a wizzy should always have the familiar with him, but not always have it following him. The resistances it gives you and the mana-regen it gives you later are invaluable. I don't even think they can be debuffed, unless your familiar is killed. That is why I tell him to "get lost" <img src='http://www.everlore.com/gimages/smile.gif' width=15 height=15 align=middle></P><P><BR>Wizard of the 53rd Circle of Knowledge.<BR>Bard of the 49th silly song.<BR>Beasty of the 20th soloing level.</P><P>"There is always one more imbecile than you had planned for."<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
